SIMPLE: plot
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plot
<hw>Plot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>plot</ets>; cf.
Goth. <ets>plats</ets> a patch. Cf. <er>Plat</er> a piece of
ground.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small extent of ground; a plat;
<as>as, a garden <ex>plot</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A plantation laid out.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Surv.)</fld> <def>A plan or draught of a field,
farm, estate, etc., drawn to a scale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plot
<hw>Plot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plotted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plotting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a plot, map, pr plan,
of; to mark the position of on a plan; to delineate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> This treatise <qex>plotteth</qex> down Cornwall as it now
standeth.</q> <rj><qau>Carew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plot
<hw>Plot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from
<ets>complot</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any scheme, stratagem,
secret design, or plan, of a complicated nature, adapted to the
accomplishment of some purpose, usually a treacherous and mischievous
one; a conspiracy; an intrigue; <as>as, the Rye-house
<ex>Plot</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have overheard a <qex>plot</qex> of death.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, think what anxious moments pass between⟦br⟧
The birth of <qex>plots</qex> and their last fatal periods!</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A share in such a plot or scheme; a participation in
any stratagem or conspiracy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And when Christ saith, Who marries the divorced commits adultery,
it is to be understood, if he had any <qex>plot</qex> in the
divorce.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Contrivance; deep reach of thought; ability to plot
or intrigue.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A man of much
<xex>plot</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Denham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A plan; a purpose.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧No other
<xex>plot</xex> in their religion but serve God and save their
souls.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>In fiction, the story of a play, novel, romance, or
poem, comprising a complication of incidents which are gradually
unfolded, sometimes by unexpected means.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the <qex>plot</qex> or intrigue must be natural, and such as
springs from the subject, then the winding up of the <qex>plot</qex>
must be a probable consequence of all that went before.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Intrigue; stratagem; conspiracy; cabal;
combination; contrivance.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1101 --></p>

<p><ent>Plot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Plot
<hw>Plot</hw> <pr>(pl⟦ocr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
form a scheme of mischief against another, especially against a
government or those who administer it; to conspire.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wicked <qex>plotteth</qex> against the just.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xxxvii. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To contrive a plan or stratagem; to
scheme.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prince did <qex>plot</qex> to be secretly gone.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Plot
<hw>Plot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To plan; to scheme; to devise; to
contrive secretly.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Plotting</xex> an unprofitable
crime.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Plotting</xex> now the fall
of others.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plotful</ent>⟦br⟧
